WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.740
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, everybody.
Welcome to another Authors at Google event.

00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:12.610
We are pleased today to welcome Mr. Jeremy
Rifkin, a well-known economist and activist.

00:00:12.610 --> 00:00:17.480
He's probably best known for his work, Where's
the Foundation on Economic Trends?

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:23.849
As well as his published works, which include
The End of Work and The Hydrogen Economy.

00:00:23.849 --> 00:00:27.529
And both topics are very relevant to the work
we do here at Google.

00:00:27.529 --> 00:00:31.789
Time magazine describes Jeremy as, "The most
hated man in science."

00:00:31.789 --> 00:00:39.410
But we love you, it's okay. Just ignore them.
Today, he'll be speaking to us on his latest

00:00:39.410 --> 00:00:45.460
book, The Empathic Civilization.
The book outlines the essential conflict between

00:00:45.460 --> 00:00:50.650
empathy and entropy -- between thinking and
doing.

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:56.510
Jeremy suggests that this arises from the
very way our consciousness is structured.

00:00:56.510 --> 00:01:02.000
And for those who have questions later, please
use the mic for the benefit of those on YouTube.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.749
And with that, my friends, please welcome
Jeremy Rifkin.

00:01:08.749 --> 00:01:13.220
&gt;&gt; [Applause]

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:26.950
Jeremy: [pause] Good afternoon, everyone.
Thank you for coming.

00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:36.350
Let me start off on a somber note, which I
hope might become a liberating reflection.

00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:42.510
I believe we may be at a seminal turning point
in the history of our species on this planet.

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:50.010
Sounds melodramatic -- I won't be here to
see it, but all of you young people in this

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:54.159
room may be a decisive generation.
Species come and go.

00:01:54.159 --> 00:02:02.100
We had two events in the last 18 months which
signaled the end game that a great industrial

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:08.229
age propelled by fossil fuels that gave us
one of the great, short-lived civilizations

00:02:08.229 --> 00:02:15.779
in history.
July 2008 -- you recall oil hit $147 a barrel

00:02:15.779 --> 00:02:20.900
on world markets.
Prices soared, inflation roared, basic items

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:26.440
became prohibitively expensive around the
world from groceries to gasoline.

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:32.919
There were food riots in 30 countries.
Purchasing power plummeted at $147 a barrel

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:38.400
all over the world.
The entire economic engine of the Industrial

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:45.900
Revolution turned off at 147 a barrel.
That was the economic meltdown. That was the

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:49.519
earthquake.
A collapse of the financial markets sixty

00:02:49.519 --> 00:02:56.829
days later, that was the aftershock.
G-20, G-8, G-2 -- our world leaders have not

00:02:56.829 --> 00:03:01.540
yet come to grips with what is really happening
to the global economy.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:06.700
Our fossil fuel energies are sunsetting. Their
S-curve is exhausted.

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:12.049
And the entire infrastructure of this civilization
is embedded in the carbon deposits of the

00:03:12.049 --> 00:03:17.459
Jurassic Age.
Our agricultural food is grown in petrochemical

00:03:17.459 --> 00:03:21.819
fertilizers and pesticides.
Almost all of our pharmaceutical products

00:03:21.819 --> 00:03:26.180
are still fossil-fuel-based.
Most of our clothes.

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:30.680
The entire construction infrastructure of
civilization is fossil-fuel-based.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:36.150
Our power transport, our heat, our light,
our logistics, our supply chain.

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:41.699
What we are seeing is the sunsetting of these
energies and the life support of the infrastructure

00:03:41.699 --> 00:03:46.709
built from them.
That's what we haven't yet come to grips with.

00:03:46.709 --> 00:03:51.249
The reason this has happened -- it's what
I call 'peak globalization' -- 147 a barrel

00:03:51.249 --> 00:03:56.099
is something called 'peak oil per capita'
not to be confused with peak oil production.

00:03:56.099 --> 00:04:00.189
They're two different things.
Peak oil per capita actually occurred over

00:04:00.189 --> 00:04:06.489
30 years ago in 1979, at the height of the
Second Industrial Revolution.

00:04:06.489 --> 00:04:10.159
In that year, had we distributed all the oil
reserves we knew we had to everyone living

00:04:10.159 --> 00:04:16.470
on the planet at that time, fairly and equitably,
that would be the most oil each person could

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:20.129
have.
We found more oil since then, but population

00:04:20.129 --> 00:04:23.430
grows quicker.
So if we distributed all the oil reserves

00:04:23.430 --> 00:04:28.629
we know we have now today to 6.8 billion people,
there's less to go around per person.

00:04:28.629 --> 00:04:32.379
So you see where I'm heading.
When China and India made their bid to bring

00:04:32.379 --> 00:04:37.979
one-third of the human race into the Industrial
Revolution propelled by and embedded into

00:04:37.979 --> 00:04:43.229
fossil fuels, the demand pressure was enormous
 -- prices went up, inflation soared, and

00:04:43.229 --> 00:04:48.759
the entire economic engine of the Industrial
Age actually shorted out at 147 a barrel.

00:04:48.759 --> 00:04:54.229
Now, you notice the economy is just slightly
starting to move again around the world.

00:04:54.229 --> 00:04:59.620
That's because we had depleted inventories.
We're replenishing them. And what's happening?

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:04.360
Oil is shooting up to $80 a barrel again.
So what I say to my colleagues is, "Show me

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:08.460
how we get through that wall."
Every time we try to regroup the global economy,

00:05:08.460 --> 00:05:12.629
based on these sunsetting energies, with a
huge amount of the developing world coming

00:05:12.629 --> 00:05:17.680
into the game, prices will go up, inflation
will roar, purchasing power will plummet at

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:19.930
about 147 a barrel, we'll keep hitting the
wall.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:25.930
That's peak globalization.
We now know the outer limits of the Industrial

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:31.039
Revolution.
We will look back at this moment as decisive.

00:05:31.039 --> 00:05:36.750
Fast forward, December 2009, Copenhagen.
Our world leaders come together to try to

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:44.460
address the entropy bill for the Industrial
Age -- the spent CO2, the exhausted energy.

00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:49.819
The U.N. Climate Panel -- our scientists tell
us that we may see a 3-degree rise in temperature

00:05:49.819 --> 00:05:55.189
on this planet -- Celsius -- in this century
because of the burning of carbon deposits

00:05:55.189 --> 00:05:58.970
over the last 200 years.
It's probably going to go much higher. That's

00:05:58.970 --> 00:06:01.540
now optimistic.
But to give you an idea of what '3-degree

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:06.210
rise' means.
A 3-degree rise in temperature in this century,

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:11.080
your century, and your children, takes us
back to the temperature on Earth 3 million

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:15.650
years ago in the Pliascene.
Different flora, different fauna, different

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:18.370
hydrological cycles.
And it's really all about the water.

00:06:18.370 --> 00:06:20.879
This is something folks really don't hear
about.

00:06:20.879 --> 00:06:26.069
For every one degree centigrade that the temperature
on the earth rises, the atmosphere can absorb

00:06:26.069 --> 00:06:30.629
and does absorb 7 percent more precipitation
 -- takes it up from the ground.

00:06:30.629 --> 00:06:36.750
That's why you're seeing more violent weather,
more floods, longer periods of droughts, wildfires.

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:42.659
Our ecosystems and our biomes have developed
over millions of years.

00:06:42.659 --> 00:06:46.030
They cannot adjust to this kind of change
this rapidly.

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:51.789
I advise the European Union.
We went to Copenhagen, and we were hoping

00:06:51.789 --> 00:06:56.960
to talk the world into mitigating CO2 at 450
parts per million by mid-century.

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:02.879
Nobody wanted to play the game.
But if we go to 450 parts per million, we

00:07:02.879 --> 00:07:08.539
were hoping we'd only go up two degrees.
Devastating, but maybe we would survive.

00:07:08.539 --> 00:07:12.009
Then James Hansen, the chief climatologist
for the United States Government threw us

00:07:12.009 --> 00:07:16.319
a curve in Brussels.
He's the head of the NASA Goddard Space Institute.

00:07:16.319 --> 00:07:21.270
Their studies show that, if we mitigate at
450 parts per million carbon by mid-century

00:07:21.270 --> 00:07:28.939
 -- your century -- we go up six degrees Celsius
according to the geological record.

00:07:28.939 --> 00:07:32.189
And the end of human civilization as we've
come to know it.

00:07:32.189 --> 00:07:39.819
We are asleep. The feedback loops are coming.
We're really in denial.

00:07:39.819 --> 00:07:43.770
Our world leaders came together in Copenhagen.
They could not cut a deal. It broke down in

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:46.710
acrimony.
The entire talks collapsed.

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:53.469
So here's my question for all of you in Google:
Why is it that our world leaders were simply

00:07:53.469 --> 00:08:01.830
unable to anticipate or respond to the meltdown
of the Industrial Revolution at 147 a barrel?

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:06.029
Still no analysis.
Why was it that our world leaders were unable

00:08:06.029 --> 00:08:11.789
to cut a deal on carbon reduction and methane
and nitrous oxide reduction at Copenhagen

00:08:11.789 --> 00:08:18.930
to address climate change even though we know
that this is imperiling our planet and threatening

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:24.310
our own species -- certainly the biggest threat
we've ever faced?

00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:29.129
The fault lies, not with just the inability
of government and business leaders to come

00:08:29.129 --> 00:08:33.830
up with new regulating mechanisms for the
global economy.

00:08:33.830 --> 00:08:38.750
The fault lies deeper than just the inability
to come up with a binding, carbon-reduction

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:45.450
target that everyone could agree to.
The fault lies with this: Our government and

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:52.500
business leaders are relying on 18th-century
ideas about human nature and the human journey

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:58.120
that were born at the beginning of the marketed,
nation-state era and spawned by the philosophers

00:08:58.120 --> 00:09:03.080
in the Enlightenment.
Those ideas are completely ill-suited for

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:09.940
the global economy and biosphere world -- your
world of the 21st century.

00:09:09.940 --> 00:09:15.490
For 1500 years, in western civilization, the
church worldview about human nature dominated.

00:09:15.490 --> 00:09:18.930
And the church said, "Little babies are born
depraved.

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:24.150
Born in sin. Born in evil.
And if we want salvation, we need to wait

00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:30.160
to the next world with salvation in Christ."
At the dawn of the market era and the nation-state

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:35.280
governance, the philosophers of Enlightenment
took that worldview on, and they came up with

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:40.460
a new set of ideas about human nature.
And those new ideas were accompanied by new

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:46.450
institutions -- market institutions, nation-state
governance, new education institutions that

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:49.600
comported with these new ideas.
What were they?

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:56.160
John Locke, the political philosopher of the
Enlightenment said, "Babies are born tabular

00:09:56.160 --> 00:10:01.630
rasa -- blank slate --" except he gave a little
opening, "There is a predisposition in human

00:10:01.630 --> 00:10:05.340
nature to acquire property."
Which is kind of funny, he kind of let that

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:07.820
one.
"And if we acquire property, we become wealthy,

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:13.930
and that's the road to happiness." Adam Smith,
the great, Scottish economist of the Enlightenment

00:10:13.930 --> 00:10:20.710
said, "Little babies are born as rational,
detached, autonomous agents.

00:10:20.710 --> 00:10:26.710
And as we grow up, we pursue our inner drive,
which is our material, self-interest in the

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:29.790
market."
The 19th century, post-Enlightenment philosophers

00:10:29.790 --> 00:10:33.380
 -- Jeremy Benton.
He said, "Little babies are born, and they

00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:39.320
seek pleasure over pain, and their core nature
is utilitarian."

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:43.820
The great naturalist, Charles Darwin, later
in the 19th century said, "Every organism,

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:49.160
every species, seeks to perpetuate themselves
and reproduce their survivor."

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:53.120
And then, of course, at the end of the 19th
century, Sigmund Freud suggested that, "Little

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:58.150
babies are born with an insatiable, erotic,
sexual desire, and they need to extinguish

00:10:58.150 --> 00:11:03.400
their libido -- that's the core drive."
Okay, now. I don't know if there are any parents

00:11:03.400 --> 00:11:06.640
in this room.
Do we have any parents in this room?

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:12.820
Please, is this what human nature is about?
That little baby -- is that little baby born

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:17.230
depraved and in sin?
Is that little baby a rational, calculating,

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:23.450
detached, autonomous agent, pursuing their
own material, utilitarian self-interest in

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:30.420
a competitive struggle to survive?
If that's who we really are -- that is our

00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:36.860
core nature -- we're likely doomed.
I don't see any scenario on the horizon in

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:43.750
which we can bring together 6.8 billion human
beings to create a seamless, integrated, sustainable,

00:11:43.750 --> 00:11:49.620
and just global economy and address climate
change and we heal the biosphere of the earth,

00:11:49.620 --> 00:11:53.880
do you?
And remember, ideas have consequences.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:59.640
Again, those ideas about human nature comported
with and accompanied the institutions that

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:02.800
justified them.
Look at our schooling system, our parenting

00:12:02.800 --> 00:12:08.260
styles, our business models.
They reflect the idea that we are aggressive,

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:14.260
utilitarian, self-interested, materialistic,
and pleasure-seeking.

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:21.130
In the last ten years, below the radar screen,
in evolutionary biology, neurocognitive science,

00:12:21.130 --> 00:12:28.930
child development, and other related fields,
our researchers are making breathtaking breakthroughs

00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:36.170
that are challenging some of the age-old assumptions
about human nature.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:41.130
Let me take you back to the early 1990s.
Sleepy little laboratory in Parma, Italy.

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:45.840
There's a macaque monkey in the laboratory,
and it got a little MRI brain scan on the

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.480
monkey.
And they're watching the monkey open up a

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:53.100
nut and seeing which neurons light up with
the brain scan.

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:57.200
By sheer serendipity -- and these are how
these things happen -- a human trainer walks

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:02.300
into the lab right after this experiment within
minutes and picks up a similar nut and tries

00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:06.450
to open it.
The macaque is gazing straight at the trainer,

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:09.410
not moving.
And when they look at the scanning machine

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:13.680
on the brain of the macaque, the same exact
neurons are lighting up when he was observing

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:17.580
someone else open the nut as when he was opening
up the nut himself.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:20.040
They were flabbergasted. They had no idea
what this was.

00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:23.810
They started to put brain scanners on other
primates, and then, humans.

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:29.430
Over and over again, they discovered something
interesting in the neural circuits of some

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:35.070
primates and all humans.
And that is, when a person experienced a certain

00:13:35.070 --> 00:13:42.430
feeling -- disgust, rejection, pleasure, joy,
frustration, anger -- certain neurons would

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:46.680
light up.
If they then observed someone else experiencing

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:51.860
those same feelings, the observer's same neurons
would light up exactly as if they were feeling

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:56.410
that other person as if it were themselves.
Now, we know this from common sense experience.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:14:01.410
If someone punctures themself and bleeds,
you have the same wince as what's going on

00:14:01.410 --> 00:14:03.860
to them.
When you see a little spider going up on someone's

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:12.570
arm, you feel a creepy feeling in your biology.
It's what we call, "empathic distress."

00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:17.970
What we are finding is that all animals that
nurse their young are social, and they have

00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:22.040
some kind of empathic distress, not just mere
neurons -- that's what we're discovering now,

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:28.080
the empathy neurons -- but a whole circuitry
that allows them to actually play and groom

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:34.320
and nurse -- social animals.
Human beings with the big neocortex were ultimately

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:37.600
social.
The worst thing you could do to a human? Ostracize

00:14:37.600 --> 00:14:41.370
them.
That little baby comes out of the womb, and

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:47.050
immediately seeking some engagement, some
reciprocity, intimacy, affection, a sense

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:53.570
of belonging.
We discovered homo empathicus. Empathy is

00:14:53.570 --> 00:14:59.000
very complicated.
When little babies are in a nursery and one

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.920
baby cries, the other babies will cry.
That's empathic distress.

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:05.870
But they don't know why they're crying.
Around two-and-a-half years of age, the baby

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:08.820
can identify themselves in the mirror and
say, "Oh, that's me.

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:15.870
That's you." Self-reflection and selfhood
go hand in hand with empathy.

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:20.410
The more I have a sense of individuality,
the more I can empathize with another individual.

00:15:20.410 --> 00:15:24.170
At around seven or eight, we learn about birth
and death.

00:15:24.170 --> 00:15:31.580
Then we know we have one and only life -- we're
fragile, we're vulnerable, we have frailties,

00:15:31.580 --> 00:15:37.090
and we understand that our life is unrepeatable.
This existential sense of ourselves that we

00:15:37.090 --> 00:15:41.790
develop, that we have one and only history
 -- we live and die -- allows us to then feel

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:45.190
that same thing in another person.
Think about when you empathize with another

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:49.990
human or another animal.
It's that feeling of death and life altogether.

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:55.411
You feel their fragility, their frailties,
their vulnerability, the one and only history,

00:15:55.411 --> 00:15:59.600
the one and only life.
And you feel their struggle to flourish and

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:03.670
be, because it's extremely hard being alive
 -- whether you're a human being or fox in

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:07.970
the wood or an ant on the ground -- it is
tough being alive.

00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:13.130
Empathy is the ability to actually feel another's
struggle.

00:16:13.130 --> 00:16:16.870
Their desire to flourish and be and then show
compassion and solidarity.

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:22.241
The most alive moments in the world are when
we feel this feeling of empathy, because we

00:16:22.241 --> 00:16:28.600
transcend ourselves, and we live in that I
zone -- kind of 'middle zone' there.

00:16:28.600 --> 00:16:32.490
By the way, empathy is the opposite of paradise
and utopia.

00:16:32.490 --> 00:16:36.070
There's no empathy in heaven.
Don't look for it; it's not there.

00:16:36.070 --> 00:16:40.160
There's no empathy in utopias, because there's
no mortality.

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:46.610
Empathy is the opposite, because it is a recognition
of life and death, our one and only journey.

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:50.620
And that's why we feel solidarity, and we
feel such an expression of transcendance with

00:16:50.620 --> 00:16:54.970
our fellow human beings.
The awe of life is right involved with that

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:59.630
empathic sensibility.
So here's the question: If we are wired for

00:16:59.630 --> 00:17:05.800
empathic distress, can we imagine a scenario
in which we could extend that central nervous

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:10.000
system -- folks here in Google -- to the entire
human race?

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.290
All of our fellow creatures in the biosphere
in which we live.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:15.910
Can you imagine that?
So now you're saying, "Oh, my God, I just

00:17:15.910 --> 00:17:19.550
gave up my lunch for this.
This guy's over the end.

00:17:19.550 --> 00:17:25.150
We can't even pass health care reform legislation.
We just had a Supreme Court that said, "You

00:17:25.150 --> 00:17:30.350
can buy any election you want in this country."
And this guy's up there talking about biosphere

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:37.020
consciousness, the human family coming together."
Well, this is the appropriate place -- Google.

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:41.790
Consciousness changes over history.
The way our brains are wired this afternoon

00:17:41.790 --> 00:17:46.160
 -- today, in the 21st century -- completely
different than a medieval serf.

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:52.790
And their brain completely different in its
wiring than an hunter/gatherer 30,000 B.C.

00:17:52.790 --> 00:17:59.100
So the question is, What is the mechanism
upon which consciousness changes over history

00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:03.760
and empathy evolves, if it does?
Because if we can find a mechanism, perhaps

00:18:03.760 --> 00:18:09.180
we could see how we could take a leap and
begin to think homo empathicus, prepare an

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:16.320
empathic civilization, create biosphere awareness.
Now, I want everyone in Google that's here

00:18:16.320 --> 00:18:20.240
in this room to concentrate with me from here
on, because you have a special mission, I

00:18:20.240 --> 00:18:24.090
think.
The great changes in consciousness in history

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:30.560
 -- they occur when two things happen.
