for the human race.
We have to be both entrepreneurial and collaborative.

00:35:53.869 --> 00:35:57.690
We have to create energy spaces that act like
social spaces on the Internet.

00:35:57.690 --> 00:36:02.150
We have to think 'commons'.
This is a revolution in thinking.

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:08.220
It changes temporal/spatial orientation.
Unless we think this is impossible -- you

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:12.940
know what I imagine, and this will resonate
with you folks here -- remember after the

00:36:12.940 --> 00:36:18.170
Iran elections that were flawed and the young
students protested in the streets and the

00:36:18.170 --> 00:36:23.669
government started to get violent by shooting?
And they shot a young, college, premed student

00:36:23.669 --> 00:36:27.079
 -- a young woman.
And someone had a cell phone, and they videoed

00:36:27.079 --> 00:36:30.730
it.
And within an hour, across the world -- because

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:35.819
of Google and all of the communications -- an
entire generation was empathizing with the

00:36:35.819 --> 00:36:40.099
young students on the streets.
That's biosphere consciousness.

00:36:40.099 --> 00:36:44.499
Today, in every school, our young people are
learning, from the time they're six or seven,

00:36:44.499 --> 00:36:49.009
that everything they do each day affects someone
else -- the food they eat, the clothes they

00:36:49.009 --> 00:36:51.790
wear, the electricity they use, the family
car.

00:36:51.790 --> 00:36:56.869
Every single thing they do actually intimately
affects the well-being of another human or

00:36:56.869 --> 00:37:03.819
another animal on this planet.
That's biosphere consciousness.

00:37:03.819 --> 00:37:07.869
The problem is, How do we break the paradox
of history -- more empathy, more entropy?

00:37:07.869 --> 00:37:12.160
A Third Industrial Revolution gives your generation
a shock, because this is distributed.

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:15.739
It's sustainable.
It's 'think global' and 'act local'.

00:37:15.739 --> 00:37:18.230
There is no guarantee you're going to get
there.

00:37:18.230 --> 00:37:22.650
I honestly don't know, when I look at all
the younger folks here, who will be around

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:26.630
in 2050 -- 2075 -- I don't know whether you're
going to make it.

00:37:26.630 --> 00:37:31.369
Our scientists say we only have a few more
years to get one roadmap for the world.

00:37:31.369 --> 00:37:34.930
No mistakes.
And we've got to get to a post-carbon era

00:37:34.930 --> 00:37:38.859
quickly.
I hope the scientists are all wrong, but I

00:37:38.859 --> 00:37:43.039
think they're underestimating the speed of
the feedback loops.

00:37:43.039 --> 00:37:47.160
So, how can consciousness change?
Let me use an example.

00:37:47.160 --> 00:37:50.829
First mirrors, and then, I want to move up
to Google maps.

00:37:50.829 --> 00:37:54.880
How many of you looked in a mirror today?
Raise your hands.

00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:59.220
You take that for granted, don't you?
Do you realize that up to the 14th, 15th century,

00:37:59.220 --> 00:38:03.859
people did not see themselves clearly?
That's why there wasn't a lot of hygiene and

00:38:03.859 --> 00:38:07.269
grooming back then.
You could see yourself in a pond of water,

00:38:07.269 --> 00:38:11.589
woe! As it's streaming down the river or in
a piece of metal.

00:38:11.589 --> 00:38:16.609
But in the 1400s in Morano or Venice, they
started mass-producing mirrors.

00:38:16.609 --> 00:38:21.640
And they took these little mirrors, and whenever
you bought a printed book, you got a mirror.

00:38:21.640 --> 00:38:25.479
All of a sudden, the new pastime -- people
started looking at themselves.

00:38:25.479 --> 00:38:31.809
"Wow, that's me." You, me.
It wasn't about narcissism.

00:38:31.809 --> 00:38:36.470
It allowed people to create self-reflection.
That's what mirrors do -- reflect.

00:38:36.470 --> 00:38:40.400
So now, we call it 'self-reflection'.
It allowed us to develop selfhood.

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:46.440
More individuality in a more existential sense
of how 'I am not you,' 'you are not I,' but

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:53.579
I can existentially support your struggle,
because I know you're a separate, individual

00:38:53.579 --> 00:38:58.249
identity.
Now, let's go up to Google.

00:38:58.249 --> 00:39:08.080
When I was young, and I remember in 1969 when
the Apollo spaceship passed the dark side

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:11.470
of the moon on the last journey, our guys
came up on the bright side.

00:39:11.470 --> 00:39:15.130
The sun is shining on the Earth and in this
ship, they took some photos of the planet

00:39:15.130 --> 00:39:18.869
Earth.
Those photos were put up on posters all over

00:39:18.869 --> 00:39:22.019
the world.
That was an out-of-body experience.

00:39:22.019 --> 00:39:28.269
Today, because of Google, you have a whole
generation that's wired their brain differently.

00:39:28.269 --> 00:39:33.999
You can take a Google map from outer space,
zoom down anywhere on this planet into the

00:39:33.999 --> 00:39:37.970
door and window of any building.
That out-of-body experience allows us to look

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:40.690
from the outside in.
From the upside down.

00:39:40.690 --> 00:39:45.989
So we get a sense of how small this is.
And how we're responsible, because we're embedded

00:39:45.989 --> 00:39:49.210
and in charge of this little sphere called
'Earth'.

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:55.849
That is truly a new change in consciousness.
People before that Google maps, they did not

00:39:55.849 --> 00:39:59.349
have that sense of framework from the outside
in and from top-down.

00:39:59.349 --> 00:40:07.210
So, can we make this in time?
What we have now is, 50 percent of the human

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:11.410
race living above our means in a nonsustainable
world with a big carbon footprint.

00:40:11.410 --> 00:40:15.880
40 percent of the human race living on two
dollars a day or less, barely able to survive.

00:40:15.880 --> 00:40:23.239
How do we bring everyone together?
How do we break the empathy/entropy paradox?

00:40:23.239 --> 00:40:28.910
I think we revisit what makes us happy.
Now remember, John Locke said, "The negation

00:40:28.910 --> 00:40:33.259
of nature, the acquisition of property, the
material wealth makes us happy."

00:40:33.259 --> 00:40:37.880
Or to quote one of the great sages of the
20th century, "Material girl, material world,"

00:40:37.880 --> 00:40:43.450
she got it wrong too, all right?
But the new happiness studies are very interesting,

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:46.170
because they're showing us, "If you're really
poor, you're not happy.

00:40:46.170 --> 00:40:51.289
You have very few emotional and empathic reserves
to think about the polar bears."

00:40:51.289 --> 00:40:55.400
As you get wealthier, you get happier.
Until you reach a threshold of what we call

00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:58.789
'basic comfort'.
That's the threshold.

00:40:58.789 --> 00:41:02.960
Beyond that, the wealthier we get, the more
unhappy we are.

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:09.779
Envy comes in, empathy goes down, we become
more insular and more isolated.

00:41:09.779 --> 00:41:13.239
So the question is, How do we take the top
half of the human race in terms of wealth

00:41:13.239 --> 00:41:17.349
and learn to live more sustainably while the
bottom half comes up to the threshold?

00:41:17.349 --> 00:41:21.369
And now, I'm going to step on some toes here
in the U.S.

00:41:21.369 --> 00:41:26.380
We got to move beyond the American Dream.
It's not suited for the biosphere world you're

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:30.800
going into.
That dream was the dream of the Enlightenment

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:35.329
philosophy, based on the idea that we're all
detached, autonomous, individual agents who

00:41:35.329 --> 00:41:40.450
pursue our self-interest and our utility.
And it worked for two centuries in a frontier

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:44.819
when the world was being colonized.
But can you imagine how we're going to bring

00:41:44.819 --> 00:41:50.979
the world together, create a global economy,
save the biosphere, with 6.8 billion cowboys

00:41:50.979 --> 00:41:59.130
each pursuing their individual self-interest?
There's a new dream emerging among your generation.

00:41:59.130 --> 00:42:03.819
It's not the American Dream.
It still -- it doesn't discount personal opportunity,

00:42:03.819 --> 00:42:09.339
but it puts it in a larger context.
If you ask young people in Europe and much

00:42:09.339 --> 00:42:15.049
of America what the dream is, I hear more
and more this term, "quality of life."

00:42:15.049 --> 00:42:19.329
We want a good quality of life.
That's a community exercise.

00:42:19.329 --> 00:42:23.849
It requires individual empowerment and community
collaboration.

00:42:23.849 --> 00:42:29.019
What you're doing on Google is, you're creating
a new frame of reference with the technology.

00:42:29.019 --> 00:42:32.329
And that is, on Google, people don't say right
or left.

00:42:32.329 --> 00:42:35.619
They talk about collaborative. They talk about
the commons.

00:42:35.619 --> 00:42:38.660
They talk about distributing and sharing knowledge,
correct?

00:42:38.660 --> 00:42:43.130
That's a sea change.
That's the beginning of biosphere consciousness.

00:42:43.130 --> 00:42:49.429
When young people saw that polar bear and
her cub on that ice flow -- that little video

00:42:49.429 --> 00:42:53.799
 -- and they knew they weren't going to make
it, an entire generation was empathizing right

00:42:53.799 --> 00:42:58.529
there at the moment, not just with the bear
and her cub on that ice flow because of climate

00:42:58.529 --> 00:43:04.489
change, but all our fellow species.
We're almost there. We're almost there.

00:43:04.489 --> 00:43:09.670
Can we get there?
I believe the mission here at Google is to

00:43:09.670 --> 00:43:15.641
take this engine, which is allowing us to
connect the central nervous system of the

00:43:15.641 --> 00:43:22.269
human race, and connect every single aspect
of this planet into a single embrace.

00:43:22.269 --> 00:43:26.809
Connect that central nervous system -- that
distributed communication -- so we can organize

00:43:26.809 --> 00:43:32.089
distributed energy, take responsibility for
the energy that bays the planet distributed

00:43:32.089 --> 00:43:35.131
our consciousness.
And finally, here's what I'd like to see here

00:43:35.131 --> 00:43:40.420
at Google: You start a global conversation
right here.

00:43:40.420 --> 00:43:44.150
What is the purpose of this Internet?
What is the purpose of Google?

00:43:44.150 --> 00:43:49.849
Is it more information?
More entertainment? Better commerce?

00:43:49.849 --> 00:43:55.391
That's all it is, that's a pretty tawdry reason
to connect the central nervous system of the

00:43:55.391 --> 00:44:00.589
human race -- I'm going to tell you that.
And if that is the case, we're going to dummy

00:44:00.589 --> 00:44:06.200
down the possibilities of saving our species.
What Google needs to do is prepare a global

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:14.880
conversation on how we began to use this new
Internet to ratchet up the conversation, to

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:20.130
begin a great, global discussion on how we
bring the human race together, create biosphere

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:27.140
consciousness, help us reduce the temperature
on the planet, think as homo empathicus.

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:32.390
Your mission, I think, is to help prepare
the groundwork for an empathic civilization.

00:44:32.390 --> 00:44:37.890
Don't squander this opportunity.
Help us lead the way into this new era.

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:40.650
I think the mission is clear.
Thank you.

00:44:40.650 --> 00:44:44.579
&gt;&gt; [Applause]

00:44:44.579 --> 00:44:53.450
&gt;&gt; I was told we should do a few minutes of
questions.

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:54.450
Anyone? Yes.

00:44:54.450 --> 00:45:00.989
Q Yeah, when we talk about these previous
revolutions, a lot of them seem to have come

00:45:00.989 --> 00:45:05.469
fairly top-down.
There was a power or wealth opportunities

00:45:05.469 --> 00:45:09.229
that were seen and seized by those who already
had capital to invest.

00:45:09.229 --> 00:45:12.009
While this one is being prevented mainly by
those people.

00:45:12.009 --> 00:45:16.660
And it doesn't look like those at the top
that have the centralized power are really

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:20.019
buying into this just yet.
And the market's going to take too long from

00:45:20.019 --> 00:45:23.690
what you're saying for this to catch up.
So I mean, how would you recommend a bottom-up

00:45:23.690 --> 00:45:24.690
revolution to this?

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:27.539
A Well, I'm starting to see it happen.
I teach at the Wharton School.

00:45:27.539 --> 00:45:30.410
I've been at there for a long time, and I
teach in the executive program.

00:45:30.410 --> 00:45:36.150
I teach CEOs -- our advanced management program.
I'm seeing a generational shift for sure.

00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:41.680
The older generation is still top-down.
Patriarchal, from parenting styles, cool models,

00:45:41.680 --> 00:45:45.819
business models, the work.
I'm seeing a younger generation in their 20's,

00:45:45.819 --> 00:45:49.700
30's, and 40's -- distributed, collaborative,
open-source.

00:45:49.700 --> 00:45:54.089
They're there.
The question is, How do we begin to bring

00:45:54.089 --> 00:45:59.529
this new, distributed thinking together in
a synergistic way so we bring distributed

00:45:59.529 --> 00:46:03.410
communication together with distributed energy
and create a distributed form of consciousness?

00:46:03.410 --> 00:46:07.339
It's going to be very difficult.
I chair something called the Global CEO Third

00:46:07.339 --> 00:46:12.109
Industrial Revolution Business Round table.
We have 125 CEOs of leading companies -- not

00:46:12.109 --> 00:46:15.400
the energy companies -- but we have all the
major, renewable energy companies.

00:46:15.400 --> 00:46:18.519
Pillar one.
The major real estate and construction companies

00:46:18.519 --> 00:46:22.229
like Cushman &amp; Wakefield and CH2M Hills in
our group.

00:46:22.229 --> 00:46:26.190
Pillar three, we got the major hydrogen companies
like UTC Hydrogenics.

00:46:26.190 --> 00:46:31.460
Pillar four, we've got IBM in our group now,
Cisco has just joined.

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:35.450
You're not, but I would love you to be.
We've got Kima in our group.

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:39.380
We've got Phillips and Schneider.
And these are CEOs at their level.

00:46:39.380 --> 00:46:43.479
And we have the major logistics company -- U.S.
postal service for example is in the group.

00:46:43.479 --> 00:46:48.359
And what we're doing now with this E.U. mandate
is, we're going into cities, regions, and

00:46:48.359 --> 00:46:53.009
countries, collaborating with major cities,
regions and countries to lay down masterplans

00:46:53.009 --> 00:46:56.450
all in the last year.
We just did San Antonio, seventh largest city

00:46:56.450 --> 00:47:00.789
in the U.S.
We're now doing Rome. Rome, the entire Rome.

00:47:00.789 --> 00:47:03.900
Third Industrial Revolution. 30 years, all
post-carbon.

00:47:03.900 --> 00:47:07.099
We just finished Monaco. We're going to Euchick
next week.

00:47:07.099 --> 00:47:10.809
We're working with Zapatero for an 8 billion
Euro rollout in Spain.

00:47:10.809 --> 00:47:15.470
We're working in Greece -- many countries.
So, I think the will is there among a whole

00:47:15.470 --> 00:47:20.979
genre of businesses that get this.
We would love to have Google right there at

00:47:20.979 --> 00:47:25.961
the center of this revolution, because you've
already extended the central nervous system.

00:47:25.961 --> 00:47:30.900
Now, you have to allow us and help us extend
the distributed energy with that central nervous

00:47:30.900 --> 00:47:35.410
system.
Tell your CEOs. Tell your senior manager.

00:47:35.410 --> 00:47:38.759
We'd love to have them with us so we can begin
to develop this process.

00:47:38.759 --> 00:47:42.099
We don't really want to wait any longer, and
we're tired of pilot projects.

00:47:42.099 --> 00:47:45.339
We want to lay down whole infrastructures
in collaboration with regions.

00:47:45.339 --> 00:47:48.819
Anyone else?

00:47:48.819 --> 00:47:58.599
Q So the E.U. is mandating things.
And you mentioned something about both being

00:47:58.599 --> 00:48:05.519
bought by corporations being allowed nowadays.
But for the first one, that doesn't sound

00:48:05.519 --> 00:48:12.809
very distributed to me.
And you're getting corporations to basically

00:48:12.809 --> 00:48:18.329
cooperate -- or governments to cooperate with
the corporations to mandate things probably

00:48:18.329 --> 00:48:22.309
on the corporation's behalf.
So how do you balance this?

00:48:22.309 --> 00:48:24.930
A I'm glad you asked.
We have a set of rules in being involved with

00:48:24.930 --> 00:48:30.990
this network for Google to know.
First of all, our CEOs are two different institutions

00:48:30.990 --> 00:48:35.239
 -- global companies and the world's cooperatives.
At first, they were uncomfortable with each

00:48:35.239 --> 00:48:37.779
other.
We have the world's banking, construction

00:48:37.779 --> 00:48:41.959
cooperatives, retail, and housing cooperatives,
because we have some litmus tests.

00:48:41.959 --> 00:48:47.019
When we go into a city or region, first of
all, there has to be three players at the

00:48:47.019 --> 00:48:52.559
table -- the civil society, the local government,
and local business, and it's a collaborative

00:48:52.559 --> 00:48:57.461
effort with them and us.
Two, whatever energy is developed there has

00:48:57.461 --> 00:49:01.819
to be developed into cooperatives -- neighborhood
cooperatives, housing cooperatives, small

00:49:01.819 --> 00:49:07.119
retail cooperatives -- so people control their
own energy and distribute it across grids.

00:49:07.119 --> 00:49:11.869
Three, our companies have to engage in new
business models like performance contracts.

00:49:11.869 --> 00:49:16.829
So for example, Phillips is in my group.
Rudy Pruvost is the CEO of Phillips Lighting.

00:49:16.829 --> 00:49:21.430
They would come in, for example, to San Francisco
and say, "We'll do your outdoor lighting if

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:26.100
the community wants it.
We'll put in compact fluorescent LED to save

00:49:26.100 --> 00:49:29.119
energy.
It's a performance contract. We'll finance

00:49:29.119 --> 00:49:32.289
it.
The city will pay us back on energy savings.

00:49:32.289 --> 00:49:38.140
If we can't do the energy savings, we lose."
So there's a whole set of new criteria.

00:49:38.140 --> 00:49:41.779
All energy has to be local.
Energy cooperatives have to be set up.

00:49:41.779 --> 00:49:47.670
Whatever businesses emerge have to be local.
And the civil society, local government, and

00:49:47.670 --> 00:49:51.789
business have to be in a joint collaborative
masterplan over a period of time with our

00:49:51.789 --> 00:49:54.070
global cooperatives and businesses.
Does that sound good to you?

00:49:54.070 --> 00:50:01.309
I don't know how else we would do it.
That engages everybody at the table -- everyone.

00:50:01.309 --> 00:50:10.279
So, my hope here is -- you've got a tremendous
opportunity here at Google.

00:50:10.279 --> 00:50:14.150
And you are privileged to be able to be at
a place where you can actually begin to roll

00:50:14.150 --> 00:50:18.940
out the technology to allow us, not only to
connect our central nervous system, but to

00:50:18.940 --> 00:50:24.650
connect our energy and connect our consciousness
and go to the next stage, which is biosphere

00:50:24.650 --> 00:50:30.130
awareness -- and begin to think about preparing
an empathic civilization.

00:50:30.130 --> 00:50:34.999
You're young, you've got the energy, don't
waste it.

00:50:34.999 --> 00:50:39.610
We need a legacy here, and that legacy is
to preserve our species, our fellow creatures,

00:50:39.610 --> 00:50:41.339
and the earth that we live in.
Thank you.

00:50:41.339 --> 00:50:41.450
